 1. Arrays :
     An array is a fixed-size data structure that stores elements of the same type in contiguous memory locations.     
      int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40};
   Internal Working:
        Arrays are stored in continuous memory
        Index-based access → O(1) (very fast)
   JVM stores:
        Base address
        Index offset calculation
   Formula: Address = base + (index * size_of_element)
   Characteristics:
          Feature    	Description
          Size	      Fixed
          Type	      Homogeneous
          Access	    Fast (O(1))
          Memory	    Contiguous
     
  Types of Arrays:
      1. Single Dimensional -int[] arr = new int[5];
      2. Multi-Dimensional -int[][] matrix = new int[3][3];
      3. Jagged Array (Different column sizes) - int[][] jagged = new int[3][];
                  jagged[0] = new int[2];
                  jagged[1] = new int[4];

Array Initialization:
   1. Declaration Only - int[] arr;
   2. Declaration + Memory Allocation - int[] arr = new int[5];
      Default values:
         Type      	Default
         int       	0
         boolean	   false
         object	    null
   3. Direct Initialization -int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
   4. Using new- int[] arr = new int[]{1, 2, 3}; ->Useful when passing to methods

  int[] arr;
  arr = {1,2,3}; // ❌ compile error
 ✔ Correct: arr = new int[]{1,2,3};

Fixed Size:
  int[] arr = new int[5]; Size = 5 (cannot change later)
  Get Size:  arr.length
  Important:
      length is a property, not method
      No parentheses
      arr.length   // ✅
      arr.length() // ❌
  Why fixed size?
      Stored in contiguous memory
      JVM allocates memory once → cannot resize

Default values trap:
      int[] arr = new int[3];
      System.out.println(arr[0]); // 0
 Memory behavior:
      Stack → reference
      Heap → actual array

  Important Methods (from Arrays class):
        Arrays.sort(arr);        
             Arrays.sort(arr);   // Sorting
        Arrays.toString(arr);   
            int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
            System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));  // Convert to String
            // [1, 2, 3]
        Arrays.binarySearch(arr, 20);
        Arrays.copyOf(arr, 10);
            int[] newArr = Arrays.copyOf(arr, 5);
        Arrays.fill(arr, 5); Fills the entire array (or part of it) with a specific value
          Arrays.fill(array, value);
          Arrays.fill(array, fromIndex, toIndex, value);
          🔸 Fill entire array
                int[] arr = new int[5];
                Arrays.fill(arr, 10);     
                System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); // [10, 10, 10, 10, 10]
          🔸 Fill partial array
               int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
               Arrays.fill(arr, 1, 4, 9); 
               System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));// [1, 9, 9, 9, 5]
               👉 fromIndex = inclusive
               👉 toIndex = exclusive
          🔥 Internal Behavior:
                 Iterates and assigns value → O(n)
                 No new array created → modifies existing array
             Works for:
                  primitives (int, char, etc.)
                  objects
                  String[] arr = new String[3];
                  Arrays.fill(arr, "java");
        Arrays.equals()
            Arrays.equals(arr1, arr2);
        Arrays.stream()
             int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
        Arrays.deepToString() (for 2D arrays)
             int[][] arr = {{1,2},{3,4}};
             System.out.println(Arrays.deepToString(arr));
    
  ✅ Advantages:
        ✔ Fast access
        ✔ Memory efficient
        ✔ Simple structure   
    ❌ Disadvantages:
        ❌ Fixed size
        ❌ Insertion/deletion costly
        ❌ No built-in dynamic behavior   
   Example:
    int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 1};
    Arrays.sort(arr); 
    for (int num : arr) {
        System.out.println(num);
    }

   Feature	     Array	     ArrayList
   Size	        Fixed	     Dynamic
   Performance	 Faster	    Slight overhead
   Methods	     Limited	   Rich API

2. Strings:
    A String is a sequence of characters.
    String str = "hello";
    IMPORTANT: String is IMMUTABLE.  Once created → cannot be changed
    String s = "hello";
    s.concat(" world");  // creates new object

  Internal Working of String:
    String Pool (Heap Memory Optimization)
    String s1 = "java";
    String s2 = "java"; -> Only one object is created in String Constant Pool
    But:  String s3 = new String("java"); -> Creates new object in heap
    
  Why String is Immutable?
      Security (used in URL, DB, file paths)
      Thread-safe
      Caching (String Pool)
      Performance
      
   Important String Methods
        str.length();
        str.charAt(0);
        str.substring(1, 3);
        str.equals("abc");
        str.equalsIgnoreCase("ABC");
        str.toUpperCase();
        str.toLowerCase();
        str.trim();
        str.contains("el");
        str.replace("l", "x");
        str.split(" ");
  
    String str = "hello world";
    String substring(int beginIndex) -> System.out.println(str.substring(6));     // world
    String substring(int beginIndex, int endIndex) -> System.out.println(str.substring(0, 5));  // hello
    beginIndex = inclusive
    endIndex = exclusive
      
    String[] split(String regex) -String[] 
    String[] split(String regex, int limit)
    🔹 Example 1 (Simple split)
        String str = "a,b,c";
        String[] arr = str.split(",");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));   // [a, b, c]
    🔹 Example 2 (Regex split)
        String str = "a1b2c3";
        String[] arr = str.split("\\d");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));  // [a, b, c]-> \\d → regex for digits  
    🔹 Example 3 (Split by multiple delimiters)
        String str = "a,b;c";
        String[] arr = str.split("[,;]");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); // [a, b, c]
    ⚠️ Common Mistake (VERY IMPORTANT)
        String str = "a.b.c"; 
        str.split(".");   // ❌ WRONG  "." in regex means any character
        ✔ Correct way: str.split("\\.");
    🔹 Example with limit
        String str = "a,b,c,d";
        String[] arr = str.split(",", 2);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));// [a, b,c,d]

  String.valueOf() - Converts different data types → String
 🔹 Syntax
    String valueOf(int i)
    String valueOf(double d)
    String valueOf(boolean b)
    String valueOf(char[] data)
    String valueOf(Object obj)
  🔸 Convert int → String
      int num = 100;
      String str = String.valueOf(num);
      System.out.println(str);  // "100"
  🔸 Convert boolean → String
     boolean flag = true;
     String str = String.valueOf(flag);
     System.out.println(str);  // "true"
  🔸 Convert char array → String
     char[] arr = {'h', 'i'};
     String str = String.valueOf(arr);     
     System.out.println(str);  // "hi"

  Why use valueOf()?
     ✔ Null-safe
     ✔ Works for all types
     ✔ Better than concatenation (+ "" trick)
  
  Important Difference:
    String.valueOf(null);   // returns "null"
    ((String) null).toString(); // ❌ NullPointerException

   valueOf() vs toString()
   Feature      	valueOf()	   toString()
   Null-safe	    ✅	          ❌
   Static	       ✅          	❌
   Usage	        Conversion	   Representation
  
 chars() method (Java 8+)
    Returns a stream of characters (as int values) from a String
  🔹 Syntax -IntStream chars()
  🔹 Example - String str = "abc";
      str.chars().forEach(System.out::println);
      Output:
      97
      98
      99 These are ASCII / Unicode values
 Convert back to characters
  String str = "abc";
  str.chars()
     .mapToObj(c -> (char) c)
     .forEach(System.out::println);
  Output:abc

  Count vowels
    String str = "hello"; 
    long count = str.chars()
        .mapToObj(c -> (char) c)
        .filter(c -> "aeiou".indexOf(c) != -1)
        .count();
    System.out.println(count);  // 2
 
Important Points:
  Returns IntStream, not Stream<Character>
  Needs conversion: (char) c

 Other Important String Methods
  🔹 toCharArray()
        String str = "java";
        char[] arr = str.toCharArray();
        ✔ Converts string → char array
        ✔ Useful in algorithms
  🔹 charAt()- str.charAt(1);  // 'a'
