String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer:
        Feature	    String	        StringBuilder    StringBuffer
        Mutability	❌ Immutable	  ✅ Mutable      ✅ Mutable
        Thread-safe	❌	            ❌              ✅
        Performance	Slow	          Fastest	         Slower than Builder

    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("hello");
    sb.append(" world");

    System.out.println(sb);  // hello world

  String Comparison (VERY IMPORTANT):
    String a = "java";
    String b = "java";
    
    System.out.println(a == b);        // true (same reference)
    System.out.println(a.equals(b));   // true (value compare)
    String x = new String("java");
    String y = new String("java");
    
    System.out.println(x == y);        // false
    System.out.println(x.equals(y));   // true

   Memory Diagram (Concept):
    String Pool: "java"  <-- s1, s2
     Heap: new String("java") <-- s3

Array vs String (Key Differences)
        Feature	      Array	              String
        Type	        Data Structure	    Class
        Mutability	  Mutable	            Immutable
        Size	        Fixed	              Fixed (but new object created on change)
        Storage	      Contiguous memory  	Heap + String Pool
        Methods	      Limited            	Rich API

  1. Why array is faster than ArrayList? -No resizing, direct memory access
  2. Why String is immutable?-> Security + caching + thread safety
  3. Why use StringBuilder? -> For heavy string modification (performance)
  4. How String pool improves performance?-> Reuses objects → reduces memory usage
  5. Why chars() returns int? -> Because Java uses Unicode (UTF-16) → char internally represented as int
